{
  "questions": [
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": "You enter a URL into your browser, but instead of the website, you immediately get a \"Server IP address could not be found\" error. However, your internet connection is perfectly fine and other common sites load instantly.",
      "question": "Which stage of the lifecycle failed?",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Spot on! If the browser cannot resolve the human-readable domain name into a machine-readable IP address, it cannot proceed any further in the request lifecycle.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "DNS Lookup"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "A TCP handshake requires a destination IP address. Because the browser couldn't resolve the domain name to an IP, it never even attempted a TCP handshake.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "TCP Handshake"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "TLS negotiation secures a connection that has already been physically established. We haven't even found the server's location yet.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "TLS Negotiation"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The browser cannot transmit an HTTP request until it has successfully connected to the server, which requires knowing its IP address first.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "HTTP Request Transmission"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "format": "sortOrder",
      "question": "Imagine you've just pressed Enter on a URL. Put the initial connection-setup events in the correct sequence before the server starts sending back the actual HTML content.",
      "items": [
